[DNA fingerprinting data of the isolates are not clearly available to confirm the relationship but cases at multiple county fairs adds to the link between the petting zoo and the illnesses. Direct contact with the animals is not required to be infected as the environment around the livestock can be the vehicle for transmission. Indeed, cases of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ (EHEC) illness have occurred linked to buildings a week or more after a petting zoo had been in them with the outbreak strain still found in the environment 42 weeks after the event underscoring the need for adequate decontamination of such sites (Varma JK, Greene KD, Reller ME, et al: An outbreak of _E. coli_ O157 following exposure to a contaminated building. JAMA 2003; 290(20): 2709-12; available at http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=197687). - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2687298,354.]
